    <h1>About</h1>
    Fjøsne et al. conducted a study to understand how earthworms influence the tiny organisms living in soil. They discovered that earthworms consistently increase certain groups of bacteria called Gammaproteobacteria, regardless of the overall mix and stability of other soil microbes. This finding is important because it shows that earthworms can change specific bacterial populations in soil, even when the general composition of soil microbes varies. Understanding these interactions helps us appreciate the complexity of soil ecosystems and the role earthworms play in maintaining soil health. This research contributes to our broader knowledge of how soil ecosystems function and could inform practices in agriculture and environmental management.
  </article>

  <article id="abstract-article-Z4YK7IIS" class="abstract-article">
    <h1>Scientific abstract</h1>
    NA; Soil represents one of the most complex microbial ecosystems on earth. It is well‐known that invertebrates such as earthworms have a major impact on transformations of organic material in soil, while their effect on the soil microbiota remains largely unknown. The aim of our work was therefore to investigate the association of earthworms with temporal stability, composition and diversity in two soil microbiota experimental series. We found that earthworms were consistently associated with an increase in subgroups of Gammaproteobacteria, despite major differences in microbiota composition and temporal stability across the experimental series. Our results therefore suggest that earthworms can affect subpopulation dynamics in the soil microbiota, irrespective of the total microbiota composition. If the soil microbiota is comprised of independent microbiota components, this can contribute to our general understanding of the complexity of the soil microbiota.
  </article>
